tell this apart from the personal name in 1 above. According to Lanfranc, archbishop of Canterbury (1070–1089), the Norman Gilbert Crispin was the first man to receive this nickname, and two of his sons adopted it as their surname. His grandson Gilbert Crispin became abbot of Westminster in 1085. Members of the Norman family were said to have inherited a shock of hair that stood up stiffly like a bristly pine, as though the name derived from Latin <i>crispus pinus</i>, but this derivation is a medieval invention."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."],"variants":[{"name":"Anni","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Anne Crespin was born in 1179, in France, her father, Guillaume III Bec Crespin Seigneur, was 50 and her mother, Eve d’Harcourt, was 39. She had at least 1 son with Robert II \"le Boiteux\" d'ESNEVAL."},"et":{"1179–":"1179–Surnud","1179–Female":"1179–Surnud","1161–1242":"1161–1242","1150–1242":"1150–1242","1220–1319":"1220–1319","1219–1275":"1219–1275","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1141–Female":"1141–Surnud","1179":"1179","1275":"1275","1220":"1220","1242":"1242","1141":"1141","1130":"1130","abt 1220":"umbes 1220","1150":"1150","1161":"1161","AFT 1150":"pärast 1150","1319":"1319","1219":"1219","França":"Prantsusmaa","Scotland":"Scotland","Criquetot-l'Esneval, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"Criquetot-l'Esneval, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1179–":"1179–Kuollut","1179–Female":"1179–Kuollut","1161–1242":"1161–1242","1150–1242":"1150–1242","1220–1319":"1220–1319","1219–1275":"1219–1275","1130–Male":"1130–Kuollut","1141–Female":"1141–Kuollut","1179":"1179","1275":"1275","1220":"1220","1242":"1242","1141":"1141","1130":"1130","abt 1220":"noin 1220","1150":"1150","1161":"1161","AFT 1150":"1150 jälkeen","1319":"1319","1219":"1219","França":"Ranska","Scotland":"Sco